	<h2>Understanding Your HOA's Authority Over Fencing</h2>
	<p>When you purchased your home in an HOA community, you agreed to the Covenants, Conditions, and Restrictions (CC&Rs) that govern your property. These legally binding documents give your HOA authority over external property modifications, including fencing. While this may feel restrictive, HOAs exist to maintain property values and neighborhood aesthetics—goals that ultimately benefit all homeowners.</p>

	<p>In California, HOAs have broad authority to regulate fencing under the Davis-Stirling Common Interest Development Act. However, this authority isn't unlimited. California Civil Code Section 4600 requires HOAs to follow their own governing documents, act reasonably, and cannot prohibit fencing that serves legitimate purposes like pool barriers or security (though they can regulate design).</p>

	<h3>Key HOA Documents You Need to Review</h3>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>CC&Rs (Covenants, Conditions & Restrictions):</strong> Primary governing document specifying fence regulations, height limits, materials, colors, and placement rules.</li>
		<li><strong>Architectural Guidelines:</strong> Detailed standards for fence design, materials, colors, and installation requirements specific to your community.</li>
		<li><strong>Bylaws:</strong> Procedures for submitting applications, review timelines, appeal processes, and enforcement mechanisms.</li>
		<li><strong>Design Standards Manual:</strong> Visual examples of approved and prohibited fence styles (if your community has one).</li>
		<li><strong>Previous Approvals:</strong> Examples of recently approved fences in your neighborhood (establish precedent).</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Where to Find These Documents:</strong> Your HOA management company, community website, or county recorder's office. California law requires HOAs to provide copies within 10 days of written request.</p>

	<h2>Common HOA Fence Restrictions in Stockton Communities</h2>

	<h3>Height Limitations</h3>
	<p><strong>Typical Stockton HOA Requirements:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Front Yard:</strong> 3-4 feet maximum (often must be open-style like picket or ornamental iron)</li>
		<li><strong>Side Yard:</strong> 6 feet maximum in most communities (some restrict to 4 feet for visible side yards)</li>
		<li><strong>Rear Yard:</strong> 6 feet maximum (most common), some communities allow 8 feet</li>
		<li><strong>Corner Lots:</strong> Often have two "front yards" with stricter height requirements</li>
		<li><strong>Pool Barriers:</strong> Minimum 4-5 feet per California law (HOAs cannot prohibit code-required pool fencing)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Material Restrictions</h3>
	<p><strong>Commonly Approved Materials in Stockton HOAs:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Wood:</strong> Cedar, redwood, or pressure-treated pine in natural stain or specified paint colors</li>
		<li><strong>Vinyl:</strong> White, tan, or colors matching home exterior (some HOAs prohibit vinyl)</li>
		<li><strong>Ornamental Iron/Aluminum:</strong> Black or bronze most common, sometimes white or custom colors</li>
		<li><strong>Composite:</strong> Increasingly accepted, especially wood-grain styles matching approved wood fences</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Commonly Prohibited Materials:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Chain link (except if hidden behind approved fencing)</li>
		<li>Corrugated metal or sheet metal</li>
		<li>Barbed wire or razor wire</li>
		<li>Chicken wire or agricultural fencing</li>
		<li>Unpainted or untreated wood</li>
		<li>Recycled/reclaimed wood (unless specific approval)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Color and Finish Requirements</h3>
	<p><strong>Typical Stockton HOA Color Standards:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Wood Fences:</strong> Natural wood stain or paint from approved color palette (often neutrals)</li>
		<li><strong>Vinyl Fences:</strong> White, beige, tan, or colors matching home trim</li>
		<li><strong>Metal Fences:</strong> Black, bronze, white, or powder-coated to match home</li>
		<li><strong>Matching Requirements:</strong> Many HOAs require fence color to complement or match house exterior</li>
		<li><strong>Approval Process:</strong> Some HOAs require paint/stain samples submitted with application</li>
